WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:02.880
Culture eats strategy for breakfast.

00:02.880 --> 00:03.720
Yeah.

00:03.720 --> 00:05.360
You have heard it, I have heard it.

00:05.360 --> 00:08.440
It's probably plastered on a poster

00:08.440 --> 00:10.000
in your break room right now,

00:10.000 --> 00:11.440
maybe peeling a little at the corners.

00:11.440 --> 00:14.600
And honestly, I kind of hate that phrase.

00:14.600 --> 00:15.440
You hate it.

00:15.440 --> 00:18.720
That's a pretty strong reaction to a business classic.

00:18.720 --> 00:19.560
I do.

00:19.560 --> 00:21.200
It just feels like one of those things consultants say

00:21.200 --> 00:23.880
when they don't really have a real answer.

00:23.880 --> 00:24.720
Right.

00:25.560 --> 00:28.160
It is catchy, sure, but what does it actually mean?

00:28.160 --> 00:30.640
It feels like a cliche that just gets thrown around

00:30.640 --> 00:33.680
in boardrooms to sort of shut down the conversation.

00:33.680 --> 00:37.960
It is basically the live laugh love of the corporate world.

00:37.960 --> 00:40.080
Okay, that is a fair critique.

00:40.080 --> 00:42.200
It has absolutely become a bumper sticker,

00:42.200 --> 00:44.040
but here's the thing about cliches,

00:44.040 --> 00:45.800
and I really hate to be the one to defend them,

00:45.800 --> 00:47.080
but usually they become cliches

00:47.080 --> 00:49.440
because there is a massive fundamental truth

00:49.440 --> 00:51.040
buried in there somewhere.

00:51.040 --> 00:52.720
We just stop hearing it

00:52.720 --> 00:54.960
because we have heard it way too often.

00:54.960 --> 00:55.960
Okay, so you were saying

00:55.960 --> 00:58.040
there is actually some meat on the bone here.

00:58.080 --> 01:00.080
There is a lot of meat,

01:00.080 --> 01:02.320
and that is exactly what we are doing today

01:02.320 --> 01:03.480
in this deep dive.

01:03.480 --> 01:05.040
We are dusting off that phrase

01:05.040 --> 01:06.640
and looking at what it actually means,

01:06.640 --> 01:09.480
not as a slogan, but as a literal survival mechanism.

01:09.480 --> 01:12.360
Right, and before we really get into the how of all this,

01:12.360 --> 01:14.880
I need to wrap my head around our source material for today.

01:14.880 --> 01:15.720
Sure.

01:15.720 --> 01:17.840
Because we are looking at insights from Jim Morgan

01:17.840 --> 01:21.840
who led applied materials.

01:21.840 --> 01:23.360
That's a massive high tech company.

01:23.360 --> 01:25.080
Right, a global tech giant.

01:25.080 --> 01:28.000
Exactly, but this analysis is being presented

01:28.000 --> 01:31.920
in a co-branded deep dive with Kalan Profits,

01:31.920 --> 01:35.120
the California Association of Non-profits.

01:35.120 --> 01:37.080
That just seems like a really odd couple to me.

01:37.080 --> 01:38.680
It does sound like a total mismatch, doesn't it?

01:38.680 --> 01:39.520
Yeah.

01:39.520 --> 01:40.560
I have this Titan of Silicon Valley,

01:40.560 --> 01:43.280
a guy who ran a hardware empire for nearly three decades,

01:43.280 --> 01:45.200
and then you have the nonprofit sector.

01:45.200 --> 01:46.720
But the reason they are paired up

01:46.720 --> 01:48.560
is really the core of our discussion today.

01:48.560 --> 01:49.560
Which is what exactly?

01:49.560 --> 01:51.840
That human behavior doesn't change

01:51.840 --> 01:53.560
just because your tax status does.

01:53.560 --> 01:55.800
Oh, wow, okay.

01:55.840 --> 01:58.800
Morgan's entire argument is that organizations,

01:58.800 --> 02:01.600
whether they are manufacturing microchips

02:01.600 --> 02:03.520
or feeding the unhoused,

02:03.520 --> 02:06.160
they all fall into the exact same traps

02:06.160 --> 02:07.560
when things get tough.

02:07.560 --> 02:09.280
Okay, let's talk about those traps then.

02:09.280 --> 02:11.640
Because usually when an organization is struggling,

02:11.640 --> 02:14.920
right, sales are down, or maybe donors are ghosting you,

02:14.920 --> 02:18.080
morale is just in the toilet.

02:18.080 --> 02:21.040
Leadership loves to pivot to strategy.

02:21.040 --> 02:23.760
Oh, we are completely addicted to strategy.

02:23.760 --> 02:26.680
It feels safe, it feels intellectual and rigorous.

02:26.680 --> 02:28.080
You hire a consultant,

02:28.080 --> 02:30.200
you draft this massive five-year plan,

02:30.200 --> 02:32.320
maybe you reorganize the whole org chart,

02:32.320 --> 02:35.520
it feels like you are doing something productive.

02:35.520 --> 02:38.680
But Morgan is saying that is the wrong move.

02:38.680 --> 02:40.480
He says it is effectively useless

02:40.480 --> 02:41.640
if your culture is broken.

02:41.640 --> 02:42.480
Useless.

02:42.480 --> 02:43.320
Completely.

02:43.320 --> 02:45.200
He argues that if the underlying system

02:45.200 --> 02:47.800
of how people actually interact with each other is flawed,

02:47.800 --> 02:50.200
no amount of brilliant strategy is gonna save you.

02:50.200 --> 02:51.520
You can have the best map in the world,

02:51.520 --> 02:53.840
but if your car has no engine, you aren't going anywhere.

02:53.840 --> 02:55.520
So the mission for today's deep dive

02:55.520 --> 02:59.520
is to explain why culture isn't just a vibe.

02:59.520 --> 03:01.120
I feel like we use that word way too much,

03:01.120 --> 03:02.840
like, oh, the culture's a bad vibe.

03:02.840 --> 03:04.680
Yeah, way too much.

03:04.680 --> 03:07.800
We want to look at it as a system of deliberate actions.

03:07.800 --> 03:11.560
And specifically, we are going to see how this applies

03:11.560 --> 03:13.400
to the nonprofit sector in California,

03:13.400 --> 03:16.120
where the stakes for you and your communities

03:16.120 --> 03:18.160
are honestly terrifyingly high.

03:18.160 --> 03:19.840
They are incredibly high.

03:19.840 --> 03:22.560
And I think we need to start by dismantling the thing

03:22.560 --> 03:26.560
most companies do instead of actually fixing their culture.

03:26.560 --> 03:27.400
The ritual.

03:27.400 --> 03:29.360
Yes, the offsite ritual.

03:29.360 --> 03:31.080
Oh, man, I know this ritual.

03:31.080 --> 03:33.680
I have lived this ritual so many times.

03:33.680 --> 03:34.520
Walk me through it.

03:34.520 --> 03:35.360
What does it look like?

03:35.360 --> 03:36.560
Okay, so the numbers are bad.

03:36.560 --> 03:37.400
Yeah.

03:37.400 --> 03:38.400
Everyone is completely stressed out.

03:38.400 --> 03:41.080
The CEO stands up and says, we have a culture problem.

03:41.080 --> 03:41.920
So what do they do?

03:41.920 --> 03:43.240
They book a hotel.

03:43.240 --> 03:44.080
Exactly.

03:44.080 --> 03:45.960
They book a hotel conference room

03:45.960 --> 03:48.600
with those terrible humming, fluorescent lights.

03:48.600 --> 03:50.520
They order some stale pastries.

03:50.520 --> 03:52.800
And they hold the offsite.

03:52.800 --> 03:54.720
The dreaded two-day offsite.

03:54.720 --> 03:55.720
Yes.

03:55.720 --> 03:59.840
You spend two whole days doing trust falls

03:59.840 --> 04:01.840
or putting sticky notes on a whiteboard.

04:01.840 --> 04:04.240
You come up with big buzzwords like synergy

04:04.240 --> 04:06.440
and excellence and innovation.

04:06.440 --> 04:08.520
And everyone feels really good for about,

04:08.520 --> 04:10.320
I don't know, six hours.

04:10.320 --> 04:11.720
It is like a sugar rush.

04:11.720 --> 04:12.720
And then what happens?

04:12.720 --> 04:15.360
Then you go back to the office on Monday morning.

04:15.360 --> 04:17.080
You open your laptop.

04:17.080 --> 04:20.240
The huge pile of work is still sitting right there.

04:20.240 --> 04:24.280
The annoying coworker is still just as annoying.

04:24.280 --> 04:26.160
And by Tuesday at lunch,

04:26.160 --> 04:28.320
that new culture is completely dead.

04:28.320 --> 04:29.160
Exactly.

04:29.160 --> 04:32.720
Morgan has seen this exact scenario a thousand times.

04:32.720 --> 04:34.440
He says the reason the offsite fails

04:34.440 --> 04:36.840
is that it treats culture as an event.

04:36.840 --> 04:37.680
An event.

04:37.680 --> 04:38.520
Yeah.

04:38.520 --> 04:40.320
You cannot change an organization's character

04:40.320 --> 04:43.000
just by telling people it needs to change for 48 hours.

04:43.000 --> 04:44.400
It feels like trying to get in shape

04:44.400 --> 04:45.880
by reading a book about jogging

04:45.880 --> 04:47.040
while you're eating a donut.

04:47.040 --> 04:48.600
That is a perfect analogy.

04:48.600 --> 04:50.920
The offsite is the book about jogging.

04:50.920 --> 04:53.320
It might help you diagnose that you are out of shape.

04:53.320 --> 04:55.360
Sure, it might even get everyone in the room

04:55.360 --> 04:57.520
to agree that jogging is a good idea.

04:57.520 --> 04:59.840
But it is not the run itself.

04:59.840 --> 05:01.880
Morgan's entire philosophy pivots

05:01.880 --> 05:03.720
on this idea of deliberate action.

05:03.720 --> 05:05.120
Deliberate action.

05:05.120 --> 05:06.560
That sounds a lot less fluffy

05:06.560 --> 05:08.640
than trust falls and sticky notes.

05:08.640 --> 05:10.520
It is basically engineering.

05:10.520 --> 05:13.560
Morgan insists that culture is built through structure,

05:13.560 --> 05:15.560
processes, and people.

05:15.560 --> 05:17.560
It is reinforced day after day

05:17.560 --> 05:20.440
in all the boring mundane stuff.

05:20.440 --> 05:23.520
It is not a feeling, it is the operating system.

05:23.520 --> 05:24.360
Oh, I like that.

05:24.360 --> 05:25.960
The offsite is just a screensaver.

05:25.960 --> 05:27.720
It looks pretty, it bounces around,

05:27.720 --> 05:30.040
but it doesn't do any of the actual processing work.

05:30.040 --> 05:31.320
That distinction is great.

05:31.320 --> 05:33.480
Operating system versus screensaver.

05:33.480 --> 05:35.400
But let me push back a little bit here.

05:35.400 --> 05:39.000
It is really easy for a billionaire tech CEO

05:39.000 --> 05:41.600
to talk about deliberate action and structure.

05:41.600 --> 05:42.440
True.

05:42.440 --> 05:43.600
He has infinite resources.

05:43.600 --> 05:46.360
He has armies of people to implement these things.

05:46.360 --> 05:48.640
We are applying this to the nonprofit sector.

05:48.640 --> 05:51.120
Does this actually translate to a small organization

05:51.120 --> 05:53.600
that is just screaching by on grants?

05:53.600 --> 05:55.480
That is the million dollar question right there.

05:55.480 --> 05:56.640
Or actually looking at the data,

05:56.640 --> 05:58.680
it's the 200 billion dollar question.

05:58.680 --> 05:59.960
Wait, 200 billion?

05:59.960 --> 06:03.000
Let's look at the actual data from count nonprofits.

06:03.000 --> 06:06.120
They released a research report called Causes Count.

06:06.120 --> 06:07.440
And I think most people,

06:07.440 --> 06:08.800
when they hear the word nonprofit,

06:08.800 --> 06:11.760
they picture a local soup kitchen or a tiny charity.

06:11.760 --> 06:13.080
They just think small.

06:13.080 --> 06:15.080
Right, just nice people doing nice things

06:15.080 --> 06:16.320
on a shoestring budget.

06:16.320 --> 06:19.520
But the reality is that the nonprofit sector in California

06:19.520 --> 06:22.360
employs over 1.2 million people.

06:22.360 --> 06:24.920
Whoa, 1.2 million.

06:24.920 --> 06:27.040
Yeah, let's put that number in perspective for you.

06:27.040 --> 06:30.200
That is bigger than the entire construction industry

06:30.200 --> 06:31.040
in California.

06:31.040 --> 06:31.880
You're kidding.

06:31.880 --> 06:34.560
No, it is bigger than the finance and insurance sectors too.

06:34.560 --> 06:37.880
It generates over $200 billion in revenue.

06:37.880 --> 06:40.960
So if the nonprofit sector has a culture crisis,

06:40.960 --> 06:42.880
it is not just a charity problem.

06:42.880 --> 06:46.280
It is a massive economic liability for the entire state.

06:46.280 --> 06:49.320
That completely changes the gravity of the conversation.

06:49.320 --> 06:51.000
We aren't just talking about making volunteers

06:51.000 --> 06:52.520
feel fuzzy and appreciated.

06:52.520 --> 06:54.120
We are talking about the efficiency

06:54.120 --> 06:56.320
of a huge chunk of the economy.

06:56.320 --> 06:58.760
Exactly, we are talking about the engine

06:58.760 --> 07:01.080
that holds the entire social safety net together.

07:01.080 --> 07:03.240
And right now it's running on broken pistons.

07:03.240 --> 07:04.720
And the source material highlights

07:04.720 --> 07:07.000
that this engine is running incredibly hot.

07:07.000 --> 07:08.760
Because they're under resourced.

07:08.760 --> 07:11.520
Right, these organizations are often under staff,

07:11.560 --> 07:13.480
underfunded, and they are dealing with some

07:13.480 --> 07:15.800
of the most difficult, heartbreaking,

07:15.800 --> 07:18.360
societal problems imaginable.

07:18.360 --> 07:22.280
Which creates a very specific, intense kind of burnout,

07:22.280 --> 07:23.120
doesn't it?

07:23.120 --> 07:24.640
Because in the corporate world,

07:24.640 --> 07:26.920
if you burn out and drop the ball,

07:26.920 --> 07:29.400
maybe you lose a quarterly bonus.

07:29.400 --> 07:32.400
But in the nonprofit world, if you burn out,

07:32.400 --> 07:35.600
maybe a vulnerable community doesn't get fed that week.

07:35.600 --> 07:37.760
The guilt factor alone must be huge.

07:37.760 --> 07:39.960
It is immense, the pressure is constant.

07:39.960 --> 07:42.120
And that leads directly to the trap we mentioned earlier

07:42.120 --> 07:43.760
with the strategy obsession.

07:43.760 --> 07:45.040
When you are that overwhelmed

07:45.040 --> 07:46.840
and you are running on fumes,

07:46.840 --> 07:49.880
your human instinct is to do something to fix it.

07:49.880 --> 07:50.720
Right.

07:50.720 --> 07:52.120
So you launch a brand new initiative.

07:52.120 --> 07:54.760
You write a new glossy strategic plan

07:54.760 --> 07:56.800
to show your donors that you are innovating.

07:56.800 --> 07:58.880
Because you always have to show impact

07:58.880 --> 08:00.120
to get the next grant.

08:00.120 --> 08:01.200
Exactly.

08:01.200 --> 08:03.960
But Morgan points out that adding a new strategic plan

08:03.960 --> 08:06.440
on top of a broken, burnt out culture

08:06.440 --> 08:08.560
is like building a second story on a house

08:08.560 --> 08:10.600
that has a crumbling foundation.

08:10.600 --> 08:12.200
It's just gonna collapse faster.

08:12.200 --> 08:13.320
Exactly.

08:13.320 --> 08:14.800
The weight of the new strategy

08:14.800 --> 08:17.520
just crushes whatever morale is left.

08:17.520 --> 08:20.920
So the solution isn't a flashier fundraising gala

08:20.920 --> 08:22.320
or a better brochure.

08:22.320 --> 08:23.320
No.

08:23.320 --> 08:25.160
The solution is to treat your culture

08:25.160 --> 08:27.520
as a core organizational asset.

08:27.520 --> 08:29.640
An asset just like your office building

08:29.640 --> 08:32.320
or your donor database or your endowment.

08:32.320 --> 08:33.160
Right.

08:33.160 --> 08:35.400
The organizations that actually thrive,

08:35.400 --> 08:36.760
the ones that retain their staff

08:36.760 --> 08:39.240
and keep donors coming back year after year

08:39.240 --> 08:41.360
are the ones that ruthlessly prioritize

08:41.360 --> 08:43.320
the internal way they work together.

08:43.320 --> 08:45.160
There is this concept of the ripple effect

08:45.160 --> 08:46.920
mentioned in the source material.

08:46.920 --> 08:50.120
And since we're talking about 10,000 member organizations

08:50.120 --> 08:51.320
and counting profits,

08:51.320 --> 08:53.600
that ripple could really be a tidal wave.

08:53.600 --> 08:55.280
Think about the sheer scale of it.

08:55.280 --> 08:57.760
If just a fraction of those 10,000 organizations

08:57.760 --> 08:59.920
improve their culture, even just incrementally,

08:59.920 --> 09:03.040
you get what Morgan calls compound interest on culture.

09:03.040 --> 09:04.520
Compound interest on culture.

09:04.520 --> 09:05.360
I love that.

09:05.360 --> 09:07.800
Because less burnout means lower turnover.

09:07.800 --> 09:11.080
And turnover is so incredibly expensive.

09:11.080 --> 09:12.880
It is devastating to a budget.

09:12.880 --> 09:16.040
Think about the recruitment costs, the training time,

09:16.040 --> 09:18.320
the lost institutional knowledge.

09:18.320 --> 09:20.640
If you fix the culture, you keep the people.

09:20.640 --> 09:22.800
If you keep the people, you keep the expertise.

09:22.800 --> 09:24.320
Which means more money and time

09:24.320 --> 09:25.960
actually goes directly to the mission.

09:25.960 --> 09:26.800
Yes.

09:26.800 --> 09:30.440
So paradoxically, stopping to fix your internal feelings

09:30.440 --> 09:32.800
and workflows is actually the most efficient,

09:32.800 --> 09:35.440
hard-nosed financial decision a leader can make.

09:35.440 --> 09:36.280
Okay.

09:36.280 --> 09:38.160
I am totally sold on the why here.

09:38.160 --> 09:40.320
Fixing culture is an efficiency strategy,

09:40.320 --> 09:41.600
plain and simple.

09:41.600 --> 09:44.200
But let's get into the how for the listeners.

09:44.200 --> 09:46.840
Because deliberate action still feels

09:46.840 --> 09:48.120
just a little vague to me.

09:48.120 --> 09:51.120
If I am a leader listening to this right now,

09:51.120 --> 09:52.400
what am I actually supposed to do

09:52.400 --> 09:54.360
on a random Tuesday morning?

09:54.360 --> 09:57.680
Like, does this start with HR at the CEO's job?

09:57.680 --> 09:58.960
This is where it gets really interesting

09:58.960 --> 10:00.680
and honestly, maybe a little uncomfortable

10:00.680 --> 10:01.920
for some of the people listening.

10:01.960 --> 10:03.720
Morgan is absolutely adamant about this.

10:03.720 --> 10:05.640
Culture starts at the board level.

10:05.640 --> 10:06.480
The board.

10:06.480 --> 10:07.320
Really?

10:07.320 --> 10:09.040
That feels so distant from the day to day.

10:09.040 --> 10:10.160
I know it does.

10:10.160 --> 10:11.960
Usually the board shows up, you know,

10:11.960 --> 10:13.680
once a quarter of the educated sandwich,

10:13.680 --> 10:16.520
they look at a spreadsheet and then they leave.

10:16.520 --> 10:20.280
How on earth do they impact the daily culture

10:20.280 --> 10:21.440
of the frontline staff?

10:21.440 --> 10:23.560
Morgan calls it tone at the top.

10:23.560 --> 10:26.320
And he isn't talking about their fun reason connections

10:26.320 --> 10:28.120
or their wealth, he is talking strictly

10:28.120 --> 10:30.400
about their behavior in those meetings.

10:30.400 --> 10:32.000
Give me a specific example.

10:32.000 --> 10:33.280
What does that look like?

10:33.280 --> 10:36.160
Okay, imagine a quarterly board meeting.

10:36.160 --> 10:37.840
The executive director is presenting

10:37.840 --> 10:39.720
a really critical report.

10:39.720 --> 10:42.000
One of the board members is just staring down,

10:42.000 --> 10:44.680
checking their email on their phone the whole time.

10:44.680 --> 10:47.040
Another one interrupts the director mid-sentence

10:47.040 --> 10:48.680
to ask a question that was already answered

10:48.680 --> 10:50.360
on page one of the packet.

10:50.360 --> 10:52.720
Okay, I am physically cringing right now

10:52.720 --> 10:55.680
because I have seen that exact scenario happen.

10:55.680 --> 10:56.800
We all have.

10:56.800 --> 10:59.800
Now, what does that behavior actually signal to the room?

10:59.800 --> 11:02.520
It signals that listening isn't important.

11:02.520 --> 11:06.200
It signals that hierarchy matters more than basic respect.

11:06.200 --> 11:09.200
It signals that we don't really care what you have to say.

11:09.200 --> 11:10.040
Wow.

11:10.040 --> 11:11.080
And that energy flows downhill.

11:11.080 --> 11:11.920
Like gravity.

11:11.920 --> 11:13.920
It is exactly like gravity.

11:13.920 --> 11:16.960
If the board treats the CEO with disrespect,

11:16.960 --> 11:20.200
the CEO is going to leave that meeting stressed out.

11:20.200 --> 11:23.000
They are more likely to be short with their VPs.

11:23.000 --> 11:25.400
The VPs take that stress out on the managers

11:25.400 --> 11:29.300
and eventually the frontline staff is absolutely miserable.

11:29.300 --> 11:30.260
That makes total sense.

11:30.260 --> 11:31.740
You cannot have a toxic board

11:31.740 --> 11:33.460
and expect a healthy staff culture.

11:33.460 --> 11:34.940
It just doesn't work.

11:34.940 --> 11:37.300
That is a pretty heavy realization

11:37.300 --> 11:40.180
because it means no amount of staff, pizza parties

11:40.180 --> 11:44.260
or employee of the month awards can fix a rot

11:44.260 --> 11:46.460
that is coming from the very top of the org chart.

11:46.460 --> 11:47.340
Precisely.

11:47.340 --> 11:48.740
You cannot train your way

11:48.740 --> 11:50.780
out of a leadership modeling problem.

11:50.780 --> 11:53.460
But, and this is a really big but,

11:53.460 --> 11:55.540
Morgan also insists that while it starts at the top,

11:55.540 --> 11:57.620
it absolutely does not stay there.

11:57.620 --> 11:58.460
What do you mean by that?

11:58.460 --> 12:00.660
He talks about this idea of collective ownership.

12:00.660 --> 12:02.860
He says it is every single team member's job

12:02.860 --> 12:03.900
to walk the talk.

12:03.900 --> 12:04.740
Okay.

12:04.740 --> 12:06.580
It isn't a special project for the HR department

12:06.580 --> 12:08.060
to just roll out and memo.

12:08.060 --> 12:09.140
Culture is what happens

12:09.140 --> 12:11.500
in every single interaction between colleagues.

12:11.500 --> 12:13.860
So it's not just the board member checking their email.

12:13.860 --> 12:16.100
It's, you know, how I respond to you

12:16.100 --> 12:17.500
when you make a mistake on a project.

12:17.500 --> 12:18.340
Exactly.

12:18.340 --> 12:19.860
Do I shame you in front of the team?

12:19.860 --> 12:23.820
Do I ignore it and fix it myself aggressively?

12:23.820 --> 12:25.260
Or do I pull you aside

12:25.260 --> 12:26.740
and help you figure out what went wrong?

12:26.740 --> 12:27.580
Right.

12:27.660 --> 12:30.620
Micro interaction, that right there is the culture.

12:30.620 --> 12:33.340
It is the aggregate of a thousand tiny decisions

12:33.340 --> 12:35.940
made by everyone every single day.

12:35.940 --> 12:38.020
You know, as we are talking about all of this,

12:38.020 --> 12:41.580
Morgan's advice, the structure, the discipline of it all,

12:41.580 --> 12:43.220
it sounds very modern.

12:43.220 --> 12:44.060
Yeah.

12:44.060 --> 12:44.880
It sounds like something you would hear

12:44.880 --> 12:46.540
at a slick TED talk in San Francisco.

12:47.420 --> 12:49.420
But reading through the deep dive materials,

12:49.420 --> 12:52.340
what really struck me is that none of this is actually new.

12:52.340 --> 12:53.860
Oh no, it is not new at all.

12:53.860 --> 12:55.140
In fact, the commentary suggests

12:55.140 --> 12:57.020
that Morgan is basically just channeling

12:57.020 --> 12:58.180
some very old ghosts here.

12:58.180 --> 12:59.020
Absolutely.

12:59.020 --> 13:01.340
And this is honestly one of my favorite parts

13:01.340 --> 13:02.820
of this entire analysis.

13:02.820 --> 13:05.380
Morgan sounds like a modern tech CEO,

13:05.380 --> 13:08.140
but he is essentially preaching ancient philosophy.

13:08.140 --> 13:09.340
I really want to dig into this

13:09.340 --> 13:12.500
because it feels like a bit of a stretch at first glance.

13:12.500 --> 13:16.540
How do we get from a Silicon Valley executive to,

13:16.540 --> 13:19.460
well, I assume we are going to ancient Greece.

13:19.460 --> 13:21.660
We are definitely going to ancient Greece.

13:21.660 --> 13:23.860
Plato and Aristotle specifically.

13:23.860 --> 13:25.260
Okay, connect those dots for me.

13:25.260 --> 13:27.700
How does Plato fit into corporate culture?

13:27.700 --> 13:29.700
Let's look at Plato's Republic.

13:29.700 --> 13:33.380
We are talking over 2,400 years ago.

13:33.380 --> 13:35.220
Plato argued that the character

13:35.220 --> 13:37.180
and the virtues of a state's leaders

13:37.180 --> 13:40.460
shape the entire society's moral fabric.

13:40.460 --> 13:42.880
Which is exactly the tone at the top concept.

13:42.880 --> 13:44.140
It is almost verbatim.

13:44.140 --> 13:45.300
Plato was basically saying,

13:45.300 --> 13:46.940
you cannot legislate greatness.

13:46.940 --> 13:50.500
You cannot write a law that simply forces people to be good.

13:50.500 --> 13:51.340
Just like Morgan says,

13:51.340 --> 13:53.940
you can't just send out a memo to create a good culture.

13:53.940 --> 13:56.060
The leader's virtue sets the ceiling

13:56.060 --> 13:57.780
for the entire organization.

13:57.780 --> 14:01.140
If the leader is corrupt or lazy, the state is corrupt.

14:01.140 --> 14:04.380
Okay, so Plato gives us the leadership modeling angles.

14:04.380 --> 14:06.140
What about the deliberate action part?

14:06.140 --> 14:07.020
Where does that come in?

14:07.020 --> 14:08.580
That is all Aristotle.

14:08.580 --> 14:10.780
In Nicomachean ethics, Aristotle argues

14:10.780 --> 14:14.060
that virtue is not a state of being, it is a habit.

14:14.060 --> 14:14.900
A habit?

14:14.900 --> 14:17.500
Yes, he has this incredibly famous idea

14:17.500 --> 14:19.820
that we are what we repeatedly do.

14:19.820 --> 14:21.580
We are what we repeatedly do.

14:21.580 --> 14:23.180
You know, that sounds like a poster too.

14:23.180 --> 14:25.740
It does, but think about the actual mechanics

14:25.740 --> 14:27.020
of what he is saying.

14:27.020 --> 14:29.780
Aristotle would have absolutely hated the corporate offside.

14:29.780 --> 14:31.620
Oh, he would have stormed out of the conference room.

14:31.620 --> 14:32.460
He would have.

14:32.460 --> 14:33.300
He would have said,

14:33.300 --> 14:36.580
you don't become brave by going to a two day seminar

14:36.580 --> 14:38.300
on the theory of bravery.

14:38.300 --> 14:41.580
You become brave by actually doing brave things

14:41.580 --> 14:43.820
repeatedly until it's natural.

14:43.820 --> 14:45.260
Right, you don't become a master pianist

14:45.260 --> 14:46.660
just by watching a concert.

14:46.660 --> 14:48.380
You have to do the scales every day.

14:48.380 --> 14:49.220
Exactly.

14:49.220 --> 14:52.100
And Morgan is saying the exact same thing to leaders today.

14:52.100 --> 14:55.100
You become a transparent, respectful organization

14:55.100 --> 14:58.180
by actually practicing transparency and respect

14:58.180 --> 15:01.460
every single day until it becomes a reflex.

15:01.460 --> 15:02.780
That makes so much sense.

15:02.780 --> 15:05.900
It takes the concept out of the realm of corporate speak

15:05.900 --> 15:09.020
and puts it right into the realm of basic human nature.

15:09.020 --> 15:10.380
I love that framing.

15:10.380 --> 15:13.060
It really validates the idea

15:13.060 --> 15:15.660
that this isn't just some passing business fad.

15:15.660 --> 15:19.620
It is literally how humans are wired to operate.

15:19.620 --> 15:23.500
But the source material also bridges this ancient wisdom

15:23.500 --> 15:27.460
to something a bit more modern and relatable than Aristotle.

15:27.460 --> 15:28.300
Yes.

15:28.300 --> 15:29.140
Sports legends.

15:29.140 --> 15:31.300
Yeah, and I think this is where the discipline aspect

15:31.300 --> 15:32.900
really shines through because sometimes

15:32.900 --> 15:35.540
when we talk about culture, it still sounds a bit soft.

15:35.540 --> 15:37.300
But then you look at someone like Pat Summit.

15:37.300 --> 15:39.700
The legendary Tennessee women's basketball coach.

15:39.700 --> 15:41.740
Right, the winningest coach in division I history

15:41.740 --> 15:42.860
at the time she retired.

15:42.860 --> 15:46.180
She did not build that absolute powerhouse

15:46.180 --> 15:48.660
of a program on vibes or just holding hands.

15:48.660 --> 15:49.500
Definitely not.

15:49.540 --> 15:51.700
She's invested on explicit, rigorous standards

15:51.700 --> 15:52.540
of accountability.

15:52.540 --> 15:55.460
She has this incredible quote that I think sums it all up.

15:55.460 --> 15:57.820
Culture isn't inspiration.

15:57.820 --> 15:59.260
It's infrastructure.

15:59.260 --> 16:01.540
Culture is infrastructure.

16:01.540 --> 16:03.220
I want to pause on that word for a second

16:03.220 --> 16:05.380
because infrastructure feels really cold.

16:05.380 --> 16:07.980
It feels like concrete and rebar and bridges.

16:07.980 --> 16:10.060
It doesn't feel like a people focused word.

16:10.060 --> 16:12.700
But that is exactly why it is so brilliant.

16:12.700 --> 16:13.940
Think about it.

16:13.940 --> 16:17.140
Infrastructure supports everything else you want to do.

16:17.180 --> 16:19.660
If the bridge is out, it doesn't matter how fast

16:19.660 --> 16:22.500
or nice your car is, you are not crossing the river.

16:22.500 --> 16:23.340
That's true.

16:23.340 --> 16:26.420
Summit meant that you build standards, how we practice,

16:26.420 --> 16:28.540
how we treat each other in the locker room,

16:28.540 --> 16:31.220
how we study film, and those standards,

16:31.220 --> 16:34.980
that infrastructure holds the weight of the team

16:34.980 --> 16:36.580
when things get really hard.

16:36.580 --> 16:38.180
So when the pressure's on in the fourth quarter

16:38.180 --> 16:40.980
of a championship game, you don't magically rise

16:40.980 --> 16:42.900
to the occasion, you just fall back

16:42.900 --> 16:44.060
to the level of your training.

16:44.060 --> 16:47.100
Exactly, you fall to the level of your infrastructure.

16:47.100 --> 16:49.420
And John Wooden is mentioned in there too, right?

16:49.420 --> 16:50.980
The famous pyramid of success.

16:50.980 --> 16:53.220
Yeah, you really can't talk about team culture

16:53.220 --> 16:55.220
without bringing up Wooden.

16:55.220 --> 16:57.380
His whole philosophy was about losing yourself

16:57.380 --> 16:58.540
for the good of the group.

16:58.540 --> 17:00.660
Which connects perfectly back to Morgan's point

17:00.660 --> 17:01.900
about collective ownership.

17:01.900 --> 17:05.580
Exactly, it is not about you being a superstar player.

17:05.580 --> 17:08.420
It is about the team functioning seamlessly

17:08.420 --> 17:10.060
as a single unit.

17:10.060 --> 17:11.520
And just to bring this all the way back

17:11.520 --> 17:13.860
to the nonprofit world for our listeners,

17:13.860 --> 17:16.700
the source also mentions Francis Husslebeam.

17:16.700 --> 17:20.060
Oh, she is an absolute giant in the nonprofit field,

17:20.060 --> 17:22.180
former CEO of the Girl Scouts.

17:22.180 --> 17:25.020
She argued that values are not just nice ideas,

17:25.020 --> 17:26.780
they are operational standards.

17:26.780 --> 17:29.500
Okay, operational standards sounds a bit jargonetomy.

17:29.500 --> 17:31.660
Can we unpack what that actually means on the ground?

17:31.660 --> 17:34.660
Sure, think of it like the speed limit on a highway.

17:34.660 --> 17:37.060
The employee handbook, which is your strategy,

17:37.060 --> 17:39.940
might say the speed limit is 55 miles per hour.

17:39.940 --> 17:42.700
But let's say the CEO drives past you

17:42.700 --> 17:44.740
every single morning doing 90,

17:44.740 --> 17:46.180
and nobody ever gets a ticket.

17:46.180 --> 17:48.500
What is the actual speed limit on that road?

17:48.500 --> 17:49.660
Well, it's 90.

17:49.660 --> 17:53.500
Exactly, the behavior completely overrides the rulebook.

17:53.500 --> 17:56.100
That behavior is the operational standard.

17:56.100 --> 17:58.860
Husslebeam, Morgan, Plato, Pat, Summit,

17:58.860 --> 18:02.260
they are all saying the exact same thing across centuries.

18:02.260 --> 18:03.100
Which is?

18:03.100 --> 18:05.620
If you say you value work-life balance in your strategy,

18:05.620 --> 18:08.140
but your operational standard is that you email your staff

18:08.140 --> 18:11.940
at 11.00 PM on a Saturday and demand an immediate answer,

18:11.940 --> 18:16.300
the 11.00 PM email wins every single time.

18:16.300 --> 18:18.820
That is the culture eats strategy moment right there,

18:18.820 --> 18:19.660
isn't it?

18:19.660 --> 18:20.500
It is.

18:20.500 --> 18:23.620
Your strategy says retain our valuable staff,

18:23.620 --> 18:25.540
but your operational standard says

18:25.540 --> 18:27.540
burn them out on the weekends.

18:27.540 --> 18:31.540
Culture wins, the staff leaves, the strategy fails.

18:31.540 --> 18:34.740
Every single time, you simply cannot fool the room.

18:34.740 --> 18:37.500
People will always believe what they see you do,

18:37.500 --> 18:39.180
not what they hear you say.

18:39.180 --> 18:40.940
All right, so we have established the problem,

18:40.980 --> 18:44.060
which is the offsite trap and the reliance on strategy.

18:44.060 --> 18:45.980
We have established the stakes,

18:45.980 --> 18:47.860
looking at the massive economic engine

18:47.860 --> 18:49.740
of the nonprofit sector,

18:49.740 --> 18:51.740
and we have connected it to the deep history

18:51.740 --> 18:54.500
of how humans have always organized themselves.

18:54.500 --> 18:56.340
But as we wrap up, I wanna leave the listener

18:56.340 --> 18:58.020
with something they can actually do today.

18:58.020 --> 19:00.140
Yes, because if we just sit here

19:00.140 --> 19:02.140
and talk about it abstractly,

19:02.140 --> 19:03.900
we are falling into the exact same trap

19:03.900 --> 19:06.100
we just spent 20 minutes criticizing.

19:06.100 --> 19:08.140
We are just having a podcast offsite.

19:08.140 --> 19:10.300
Exactly, I don't wanna just talk about jogging.

19:10.300 --> 19:11.860
I want everyone to put on their shoes.

19:11.860 --> 19:12.980
Yeah.

19:12.980 --> 19:15.340
So Morgan has a very specific challenge

19:15.340 --> 19:16.740
for you, the listener,

19:16.740 --> 19:18.780
and I have to be completely honest.

19:18.780 --> 19:21.980
When I read this in the deep dive,

19:21.980 --> 19:23.460
my stomach dropped a little bit.

19:23.460 --> 19:24.500
It is intimidating.

19:24.500 --> 19:26.980
It sounds so simple,

19:26.980 --> 19:30.620
but it sounds genuinely scary for a leader to actually do.

19:30.620 --> 19:32.900
It is terrifying if you do it right,

19:32.900 --> 19:34.580
but it is really the only way

19:34.580 --> 19:38.020
to get an honest baseline of your current infrastructure.

19:38.020 --> 19:40.500
Okay, so here is the exercise for you.

19:41.580 --> 19:42.860
Sometime this week,

19:42.860 --> 19:45.980
find three people in your organization,

19:45.980 --> 19:47.980
but, and this is the crucial part,

19:47.980 --> 19:50.020
do not ask your direct reports.

19:50.020 --> 19:51.540
Right, because if you ask the people

19:51.540 --> 19:53.100
whose performance reviews you write,

19:53.100 --> 19:55.020
they are gonna tell you exactly what you wanna hear.

19:55.020 --> 19:56.340
Right, self-preservation.

19:56.340 --> 19:57.620
You need to go deeper,

19:57.620 --> 19:59.620
go a level or two down the work chart,

19:59.620 --> 20:01.740
or ask people in a completely different department.

20:01.740 --> 20:04.020
You have to get out of your immediate echo chamber.

20:04.020 --> 20:05.980
Okay, so you find these three people

20:05.980 --> 20:08.220
and you ask them one simple question, ready?

20:08.220 --> 20:09.380
The question is,

20:09.380 --> 20:11.900
what is one thing about how we work together

20:11.900 --> 20:13.540
that we say we value,

20:13.540 --> 20:15.100
but we don't actually do?

20:15.100 --> 20:18.300
Yeah, that right there is the seto gap.

20:18.300 --> 20:19.460
And here is the rule,

20:19.460 --> 20:21.260
which I think is definitely the hardest part

20:21.260 --> 20:22.820
of the whole exercise.

20:22.820 --> 20:24.020
You have to just listen.

20:24.020 --> 20:25.740
You cannot defend yourself.

20:25.740 --> 20:28.500
You cannot explain away their answer.

20:28.500 --> 20:29.780
That is the killer.

20:29.780 --> 20:31.620
The urge to explain is so strong.

20:31.620 --> 20:32.700
Oh, it really is.

20:32.700 --> 20:34.180
If they look at you and say,

20:34.180 --> 20:36.300
well, we say we value transparency,

20:36.300 --> 20:39.580
but all the real decisions are made behind closed doors.

20:39.580 --> 20:41.140
You cannot say, well, actually,

20:41.140 --> 20:43.660
that was because of specific legal issue.

20:43.660 --> 20:46.140
You just have to nod and say, thank you for telling me.

20:46.140 --> 20:47.900
And that uncomfortable silence?

20:47.900 --> 20:50.180
That is where the actual learning happens,

20:50.180 --> 20:51.780
because whatever they tell you,

20:51.780 --> 20:54.780
that specific gap between the shiny poster on the wall

20:54.780 --> 20:56.940
and the messy reality on the ground,

20:56.940 --> 20:59.020
that is where your culture actually lives.

20:59.020 --> 20:59.860
Wow.

20:59.860 --> 21:01.220
That gap is your culture.

21:01.220 --> 21:03.380
It is a massive reality check.

21:03.380 --> 21:06.740
And I can completely see why leaders avoid doing this.

21:06.740 --> 21:08.500
Who wants to voluntarily hear

21:08.500 --> 21:10.700
that they aren't living up to their own stated values?

21:10.700 --> 21:12.060
Nobody wants to hear that.

21:12.060 --> 21:13.460
It hurts your ego.

21:13.460 --> 21:15.540
But for the Count and Profits members listening to this,

21:15.540 --> 21:17.420
or really anyone leading a team,

21:17.420 --> 21:19.900
imagine if every leader did that this week.

21:19.900 --> 21:20.740
The ripple effect.

21:20.740 --> 21:21.560
Exactly.

21:21.560 --> 21:23.380
Imagine the uncomfortable,

21:23.380 --> 21:25.380
but entirely necessary conversations

21:25.380 --> 21:27.020
that would finally start happening.

21:27.020 --> 21:30.940
That is the exact deliberate action Morgan is talking about.

21:30.940 --> 21:32.940
It starts with facing reality.

21:32.940 --> 21:35.740
It starts with facing the reality of your current culture,

21:35.740 --> 21:37.380
not the fantasy version you put

21:37.380 --> 21:39.860
on the About Us page of your website.

21:39.860 --> 21:42.580
It reminds me of that one quote from the source material.

21:42.580 --> 21:46.120
Morgan says, every organization already has a culture.

21:46.120 --> 21:48.660
The only question is whether it's the one they want.

21:48.660 --> 21:49.540
Exactly.

21:49.540 --> 21:51.700
And that is the final thought I really want

21:51.700 --> 21:53.920
everyone to sit with today.

21:53.920 --> 21:56.780
You don't get to choose whether you have a culture or not.

21:56.780 --> 21:58.540
You have one right now.

21:58.540 --> 22:00.340
It is forming while we speak.

22:00.340 --> 22:02.280
It is forming in your Slack channels.

22:02.280 --> 22:03.880
It's forming in your Zoom chats,

22:03.880 --> 22:05.320
in the hallway conversations,

22:05.320 --> 22:07.440
and the way you structure your meeting agendas.

22:07.440 --> 22:08.720
It is never neutral.

22:08.720 --> 22:10.240
It is never, ever neutral.

22:10.240 --> 22:12.520
Every single interaction is either building

22:12.520 --> 22:15.080
the culture you want or it is destroying it.

22:15.080 --> 22:16.320
It is compound interest,

22:16.320 --> 22:18.880
and it's accumulating every second of every day.

22:18.880 --> 22:19.800
That is powerful.

22:19.800 --> 22:21.680
We are all architects of this stuff,

22:21.680 --> 22:23.440
whether we realize it or not.

22:23.440 --> 22:24.600
But let me add one more thought

22:24.600 --> 22:25.920
for you to show on before we go.

22:25.920 --> 22:26.760
Okay.

22:26.760 --> 22:28.680
When you go out and ask those three people

22:28.680 --> 22:31.140
that scary say-to-gap question this week,

22:32.020 --> 22:34.260
pay close attention if they hesitate.

22:34.260 --> 22:35.420
Oh, that's good.

22:35.420 --> 22:38.340
What if the silence you hear when you ask that question

22:38.340 --> 22:41.140
is actually the loudest part of your culture?

22:41.140 --> 22:44.100
If they are too afraid to even answer you honestly,

22:44.100 --> 22:46.220
that tells you everything you need to know

22:46.220 --> 22:47.980
about your infrastructure.

22:47.980 --> 22:49.780
That is a brilliant point.

22:49.780 --> 22:52.100
If fear is your operational standard,

22:52.100 --> 22:54.500
no strategy can save you.

22:54.500 --> 22:57.460
So the real question isn't, do we have a culture?

22:57.460 --> 23:00.220
The question is, is this the one we intended to build?

23:00.220 --> 23:01.060
Right.

23:01.060 --> 23:01.940
If the answer is no,

23:01.940 --> 23:03.780
then you need to cancel the offsite,

23:03.780 --> 23:05.180
stop printing the coffee mugs,

23:05.180 --> 23:07.380
and start looking really closely at your daily habits.

23:07.380 --> 23:09.740
Start looking at the speed limit you are actually driving.

23:09.740 --> 23:11.140
Deliberate action.

23:11.140 --> 23:12.820
That is the true takeaway here.

23:12.820 --> 23:15.300
Thank you so much for walking us through this deep dive.

23:15.300 --> 23:17.940
It has definitely made me rethink how I approach

23:17.940 --> 23:21.820
my own team and maybe my own emails on the weekend.

23:21.820 --> 23:22.660
My pleasure.

23:22.660 --> 23:25.740
Just please, don't send the middle 11, 0 p.m.

23:25.740 --> 23:27.180
I will do my absolute best.

23:27.180 --> 23:28.540
And to you, the listener.

23:28.540 --> 23:30.460
Good luck with those three questions this week.

23:30.460 --> 23:31.940
It might be tough, but remember,

23:31.940 --> 23:33.540
culture eats strategy for breakfast.

23:33.540 --> 23:36.180
You might as well make sure it is a healthy breakfast.

23:36.180 --> 23:38.180
Thanks for joining us on this deep dive.

